	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>A new vision for the sustainable management of African fisheries</h1>

			
			<h4>
												19 September 2005
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> A paper, to be submitted at the NEPAD ‘Fish for All’ meeting in Abuja, at the end of August 2005, entitled ‘Vers une nouvelle vision pour l'exploitation et la gestion durable de la richesse halieutique Africaine’ (‘Towards a new vision for sustainable management and exploitation of African fish resources’) has just been published.</p><p> The paper argues that current fisheries policies and management measures are based on an ‘ancient’ vision, oriented towards production, where what matters is the quantity of fish caught. In Africa, as in other places, this vision has led to over-capacity in the industrial and artisanal sectors, without answering African countries’ concerns, such as food security and poverty alleviation.</p><p> The paper then advocates a new, more coherent, vision, based on the economic nature of the fishing activity. In particular, it denies that African small-scale fisheries is an ‘activity for the poor’, and insists that these small-scale fisheries should be considered as what they are: an economic activity, enabling economic development.</p><p> This new vision is based on a valuation of the potential wealth that fish resources represent. The paper argues that a prerequisite condition for creating such wealth in a sustainable manner is to have appropriate management systems. Trying to create wealth from fisheries, through, for example, developing exports for lucrative markets, before having proper management in place will inevitably lead to failure.</p><p> Highlighting the need for management systems as a priority, it then suggests that investment should first and foremost be used to implement them. This is something that NEPAD should take on board. The authors also consider that the NEPAD summit could initiate this change of vision, particularly by adopting the concept of MEY (maximum economic yield) rather than MSY (maximum sustainable yield). According to them, MEY is a more appropriate concept for the new vision they are proposing.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p> Paper by Moctar Bâ, Abdellatif Berraho, Clotilde Bodiguel, Stephen Cunningham and Yunus Mgaya`</p><p>

<a href="http://www.fishforall.org/ffa-summit/NEPAD_Coastal_and_Marine_Paper.pdf" target="_self">http://www.fishforall.org/ffa-summit/NEPAD_Coastal_and_Marine_Paper.pdf</a> <br/> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> Whilst it does not suggest many practical actions to be taken by NEPAD, this paper deserves the attention of participants at the ‘Fish for All’ meeting, given the need for a rapid change in attitude towards fisheries management, and a context of general over-capacity in the means of production.</p><p> The authors question the rationale of current fisheries management - the ‘productionist and technologist’ approach - and emphasise the importance in their ‘new vision’ of such issues as the participation of stakeholders, providing appropriate information for effective fisheries management. This raises further questions about current management practices, which tend to overlook, or attach little importance to these elements.</p><p> Such an approach would provide some useful reflections on ACP-EU FPAs. The production aspects of these partnerships - the fishing possibilities - should become of secondary importance to considerations as to how the EU can support the creation, in a sustainable manner, of wealth from ACP fish through support for training, value adding, etc, and support to management measures. This is particularly important in cases where ACP resources are already showing signs of overexploitation.</p><p> It would strongly question the existing linkages between the amount of financial compensation provided and the level of fishing possibilities granted: in cases where ACP marine ecosystems and resources are overexploited, a partnership would mean providing more financial and technical support for fewer fishing possibilities.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
